Title:
Ferrum (Windows-first vulnerability research & security auditing framework)

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
Ferrum is a single-binary Windows-focused security auditing and vulnerability research framework written in Go (`ferrum.exe`). It provides a modular architecture where research modules are registered via a small core interface and executed through a CLI. The project targets Windows attack-surface enumeration and triage for local privilege escalation (LPE), persistence opportunities, and COM hijacking scenarios. A highlighted capability is a `--CLSID` module that models a ProcMon-style filter workflow to identify COM registration lookups that fall back to user-writable HKCU class registrations (useful for hijack/LPE hunting). It supports running individual modules or all modules and writing reports to files/folders for later analysis. It’s primarily useful for red teamers, pentesters, and Windows security researchers doing host-based enumeration and exploit/persistence research.

Technical Focus:
- Modular Go framework design (module registration via `core.Module` / `core.Register`)
- Windows API interaction via build-tagged wrappers (`windows/`)
- COM/CLSID enumeration and hijack triage (InprocServer32/LocalServer32)
- LPE and persistence attack-surface auditing on Windows
- Report generation and batch module execution (`--ALL`, `--OUTPUT`)

Use Cases:
- Enumerate COM/CLSID registration behaviors to spot HKCU-based hijack candidates
- Baseline and audit Windows endpoints for common LPE/persistence misconfigurations
- Automate host triage by running a suite of research modules and exporting reports
- Build and extend custom Windows research modules in Go within a unified CLI tool

Keywords:
Ferrum, Windows, Go, vulnerability research, security auditing, LPE, local privilege escalation, persistence, COM hijacking, CLSID, HKCU\Software\Classes, InprocServer32, LocalServer32, ProcMon, enumeration, UAC bypass, Windows API, modular framework, single binary, reporting